# IMPLEMENTATION RULES - NON-NEGOTIABLE

The project is judged by completed business workflows, not by architectural coverage. A workflow that produces a real result is worth more than ten unimplemented modules.

You are building production software, not architectural demonstrations.

The following are highly prohibited at all times:

* placeholder services
* mock implementations
* fake repositories
* TODO handlers
* simulated API responses
* hardcoded sample data
* stub modules
* "future implementation" comments
* demo-only workflows
* prototype logic

Every module must perform real work.

If a feature depends on external data:

* connect to a real source
* implement the retrieval logic
* implement validation
* implement error handling

If a feature cannot yet be implemented because a dependency is missing:

DO NOT create a fake implementation.

Instead:

1. Clearly identify the missing dependency.
2. Document why implementation cannot proceed.
3. Stop implementation at that boundary.

Never hide missing functionality behind mock code.

Definition of Done:

A module is considered complete only when:

* inputs are accepted
* processing occurs
* outputs are produced
* errors are handled
* the feature performs its intended business function

Examples:

BAD:
LeadDiscoveryService returns 50 sample businesses.

GOOD:
LeadDiscoveryService retrieves actual businesses from configured discovery providers.

BAD:
TikTokProvider returns mocked profiles.

GOOD:
TikTokProvider performs real discovery and returns real profiles.

BAD:
VideoRenderService simulates rendering.

GOOD:
VideoRenderService invokes Remotion and produces an actual MP4.

Implementation completeness is prioritized over architectural completeness.

Prefer:

All modules working 

Every pull request must answer:

"What real business operation does this code perform today?"

If the answer is "none", the implementation is incomplete.
